aches to some tense phenonema. Although time is a universal dimension of the human experience, some languages encode reference to time without any grammatical tense morphology of the verb. Some of these exceptional “tenseless” languages are investigated in this volume: Kalaallisut, Paraguayan Guaraní and Movima. Modal verbs are polyfunctional in the sense that they express both tense and modality. In this volume, an untypical modal is analyzed, a modal analysis of imperatives is argued for, and sentential mood, which is closely related to modality, is analyzed. It is always interesting to look at the expression of tense in understudied languages, which is done here for Scottish Gaelic, Austronesian Rukai and German dialects. The volume can be used for graduate and undergraduate level teaching  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxTense. 4aMorphologie. 4aSemantik. 4aSyntax. 4aTypologie /Sprache. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMorphology.  aSemantics.  aSyntax.  aTypology / Language.1 aBittner, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Cheng-Fu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemirdache, Hamida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiannakidou, Anastasia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaude, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandgraf, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLungu, Oana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusan, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusan, Renate, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/